            <h3>Penicillins</h3>
            <p>The first antibiotic to be discovered and one of the most famous, penicillin was discovered by chance in 1928 when Dr Alexander Fleming returned from a holiday and found mould growing on a Petri dish of bacteria in the lab, killing bacteria around it with antibiotics. Although promising, the discovery was overlooked by other scientists due to the difficulty of production and would not be developed until 1937 by another team of scientists. Producing enough penicillin for even a single patient would remain an issue until 1941, when fermentation vats with corn byproducts and new mould strains were used to produce larger amounts of the antibiotic, saving the lives of many injured soldiers during WW2.</p>
            <p>Penicillin is a beta-lactam antibiotic, binding to bacterial cell walls to stop growth and repair, which results in cell walls becoming weaker over time and letting in water until the cells burst. While effective, some bacteria do not have a cell wall and are not affected by penicillin, while other bacteria might be resistant to penicillin due to adaptations like beta-lactamase enzymes which break down antibiotics.</p>
