            <h3>Tetracyclines</h3>
            <p>Tetracyclines are a class of antibiotic that has actually been used before the discovery of antibiotics, having occurred naturally in the diets of ancient Sudanese Nubian people in 350 CE, and potentially keeping their rate of disease infection low. A broad-spectrum antibiotic that works against many different types of bacteria, notably cholera, plague, malaria, syphilis and MRSA, tetracyclines are nevertheless also subject to antibiotic resistance and should be used carefully, even though they are commonly used.</p>
            <p>Tetracyclines are protein synthesis inhibitors, preventing bacterial cells from producing protein cell components by keeping ribosomes and tRNA base transporters apart.</p>
